Specific the treatment groups and Build up hypothesis

Control group(C): almond yogurt

Fortified group(F): almond yogurt with fortified vitamin D and calcium citrate

ho=there is no difference btw control group and fortified group in pH during 10 weeks shelf life.

Specify the sample sizes, means, and variances for each group that would be reasonable if your hypothesis were true.

weeks<- 1:10
groups<-rep(c("C","F"),each=10)
pH<- c(rnorm(10,4.4,0.1),rnorm(10,4.5,0.1))
mydata1 <- data.frame(weeks,groups,pH)

Analyze data

Q1 whether there is difference in pH between groups during the 10 weeks shelf-life (independed test)and use boxplot to vistulize the results

t.test(mydata1$pH~mydata1$groups)   
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  mydata1$pH by mydata1$groups
## t = -1.2423, df = 14.505, p-value = 0.2338
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -0.22544327  0.05972679
## sample estimates:
## mean in group C mean in group F 
##        4.401363        4.484222
boxplot(mydata1$pH~mydata1$groups)

#### Q2 The changes of pH in both groups in 10 weeks storage

library(ggplot2)
ggplot(mydata1, aes(x=weeks, y=pH,color=groups)) +
  geom_point()+
  geom_smooth(se=FALSE)+
  scale_x_continuous(breaks=seq(1,10,by=1))+
  scale_y_continuous(breaks=seq(4.0,5,by=0.1))
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

### Ajust the means of different groups with same sample size

weeks<- 1:10
groups<-rep(c("C","F"),each=10)
pH<- c(rnorm(10,4.4,0.05),rnorm(10,4.5,0.05))
mydata1 <- data.frame(weeks,groups,pH)
t.test(mydata1$pH~mydata1$groups) # when the sample size is 10, the difference are significantly influenced by the variance.   
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  mydata1$pH by mydata1$groups
## t = -4.3377, df = 14.615, p-value = 0.0006202
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -0.12953030 -0.04404335
## sample estimates:
## mean in group C mean in group F 
##        4.399429        4.486216
boxplot(mydata1$pH~mydata1$groups)
